'''DSP-4''', or '''N-(2-chloroethyl)-N-ethyl-2-bromobenzylamine''', is a [[neurotoxin]] selective for [[noradrenergic]] neurons, capable of crossing the [[blood–brain barrier]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Daw NW, Videen TO, Parkinson D, Rader RK |title=DSP-4 (N-(2-Chloroethyl)-N-ethyl-2-bromobenzylamine) Depletes Noradrenaline in Kitten Visual Cortex Without Altering the Effects of Monocular Deprivation |journal=J. Neurosci. |volume=5 |issue=7 |pages=1925–1933 |year=1985 |pmid=3926960}}</ref>
It exerts transient effects in peripheral sympathetic neurons, but more permanent changes within neurons of the [[central nervous system]]. It can induce long-term depletion in cortical and spinal levels of noradrenaline.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jaim-Etcheverry G, Mari'a Zieher L |title=DSP-4: A novel compound with neurotoxic effects on noradrenergic neurons of adult and developing rats |journal=Brain Res. |volume=188 |issue=2 |pages=513–523 |year=1980 |pmid=7370771 |doi=10.1016/0006-8993(80)90049-9}}</ref>
